AGI -&nbsp; If it is not arginate, Russian President Vladimir Putin, after having invaded Ukraine in 2022, "will move without doubt on Moldova and perhaps even on Romania". In an interview with several newspapers (La Tribune Dimanche, Le JDD, Le Parisien and Ouest-France).&nbsp; The possible "disappearance" of the United States from Ukraine "is not in their interest", said the French president, because "what the United States has done over the last three years is entirely diplomatic and military in line with their tradition." If Washington agrees to "sign a ceasefire without any security guarantee for Ukraine", then its "capacity of geostrategic deterrence towards Russia, China and others would fade the same day", he argued.&nbsp;
After the White House fight, Macron said he invited Trump and Zelensky "to calm". "I think that, beyond anger, everyone needs to return to calm, respect and recognition," said the French President. According to the Elysée, he would have spoken with each of his Ukrainian and American counterparts on Friday evening. Macron then had &nbsp;colloquial with British Prime Minister Keir Starmer, European Council President Antonio Costa and NATO Secretary-General Mark Rutte to prepare the summit that on Sunday will gather around 15 European leaders in London to reaffirm support in Kiev, as well as the EU's extraordinary defence summit on March 6.
<h2> &nbsp;</h2>
<h2> Macron hopes for European joint funding
In the interview with several Sunday newspapers, French President Emmanuel Macron hopes that the European Union countries will make rapid progress towards a "massive and joint financing" equal to "million billion euro" to build a common defence. The 27 will meet again in Brussels on Thursday for a summit.
&nbsp;
"We will give the European Commission the mandate to define the capacity requirements for the construction of a common defence," because 'we must mobilize common funding for hundreds of billions of euros' and make it 'hopefully', said at Le Parisien. The interview was released at Le Parisien, La Tribune Dimanche, Le Journal du Dimanche (JDD) and Ouest-France. In order to obtain an independent European defence from NATO, "it will take 5 years, 10 years, but it is nothing," warned the French President, quoted by JDD. "I believe today is the time for a strategic awakening, because in all countries there is confusion and uncertainty about long-term American support," he added. France has been supporting the construction of a European defence system independent of NATO and the US for years.
&nbsp;
Macron believes that Trump's return to the White House, which raises the risk of an American distrust from Europe, offers the prospect of progress in this field. The future German Chancellor, Friedrich Merz, said he was ready to break with 80 years of Atlanticist tradition in defence matters and assured that security in Europe will be "an absolute priority in the coming weeks".
&nbsp;
The concern of many EU countries was accentuated by yesterday's verbal confrontation at the White House between Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky and US President Donald Trump. Volodymyr Zelensky is one of the approximately fifteen European leaders that will meet in London on the invitation of British Prime Minister Keir Starmer. The Heads of State and Government of the European Union will meet Thursday in Brussels for a special summit dedicated to Ukraine and European security issues.&nbsp;

